'''Peter Wallace''' ({{floruit|1638}}) is commonly held to have been an English or Scottish [[buccaneer]] who, in 1638 aboard the ''Swallow'', founded the first English settlement in present-day [[Belize]].
==Buccaneering==
In 1638, Wallace is believed to have landed at Swallow Caye aboard the ''Swallow'', with a crew of some 80 British men. This is often regarded as the first non-Mayan, non-Hispanic settlement in present-day Belize.{{sfn|Winzerling|1946|p=x}}{{sfn|Ancona|1877|pp=5-8}}{{sfn|Ancona|1878|pp=371-373}}{{sfn|Asturias|1925|p=7-9, 11}}{{sfn|Craig|1969|p=55}}{{sfn|Curry|1956|p=32}}{{sfn|Donohoe|1964|pp=27-28}}{{sfn|Gibbs|1883|pp=21-22}}{{sfn|Griffith|Alford|Bolland|2022|loc=third para}}{{sfn|Kinsbruner|Langer|2008|loc=first para}}{{sfn|Waight|2022|loc=second to fourth para}}<ref group="note">Variations of this story exist. For instance, {{harvnb|''anon.''|1829|p=40}} states {{blockquote|text=1638. ---- This year a few British subjects first inhabited Honduras, having been wrecked on the Coast.}} (which story is accepted by {{harvnb|Avery|1900|p=333}}, by {{harvnb|Bristowe|Wright|1888|p=23}}, by {{harvnb|Wayne|1917|p=162}}, and [broadly] by {{harvnb|Gibbs|1883|p=22}}), while {{harvnb|''anon.''|1828|p=4}} (quoting {{harvnb|''anon.''|1826}}) states {{blockquote|text=The British Settlement of Honduras, of which Belize is the capital, cannot be traced to be of any greater antiquity than from the administration of Oliver Cromwell, in Great Britain, at which period it was, from its remote and secret situation, used by the English, rather as a place of refuge and concealment, from the dreadful and savage warfare then carried on by the Spaniards ... .}} (which story is accepted by {{harvnb|Temple|1857|p=116}}), whereas {{harvnb|Ancona|1877|pp=7-8}} states # (quoting a column entitled ''Ojeada histórica sobre el establecimiento británico de Belice'' in the ''Fénix'' newspaper by [[Justo Sierra]]) that Wallace landed in the mid-17th century at the mouth of the Belize River, where he and his crew built defensive trenches (accepted by {{harvnb|Peniche|1869|pp=218-219}}, and by {{harvnb|Rubio Alpuche|1894|p=34}}), # (quoting a biography of [[Antonio de Figueroa y Silva]] by [[Crescencio Carrillo]]) that Wallace led British buccaneers from their base in Laguna de Terminos to the Belize River in 1717 (repeated in {{harvnb|Carillo y Ancona|1878|pp=260-261}}), # (quoting a geographical dictionary by Ungewitter) that Wallace landed in 1640 (accepted by {{harvnb|Craig|1969|p=55}} and {{harvnb|Winzerling|1946|pp=53-56}}), # (quoting a geographical dictionary by Egli) that Wallace landed in 1610, # (quoting a geographical dictionary by MacCulloch) that Wallace landed after the signing of the [[Treaty of Madrid (1667)|Earl of Sandwich's Treaty]] on 23 May 1667, while {{harvnb|Asturias|1925|pp=8-9, 11}} states that Wallace landed in 1603 or 1604.</ref>
==Legacy==
===Social===
'Belize' is commonly held to be a corruption of 'Wallace' or 'Wallis.'{{sfn|Ancona|1877|pp=5-7}}{{sfn|Bristowe|Wright|1888|p=23}}{{sfn|Craig|1969|p=55}}{{sfn|Donohoe|1964|pp=27-28}}{{sfn|Gibbs|1883|pp=21-22}}{{sfn|Griffith|Alford|Bolland|2022|loc=third para}}{{sfn|Kinsbruner|Langer|2008|loc=first para}}{{sfn|Morris|1883|pp=12-13}}{{sfn|Waight|2022|loc=first para}}<ref group="note">For instance, the following variants of 'Wallace' or 'Wallis' appear in Spanish records– 'Walis,' 'Wallix,' 'Valiss,' 'Valiz,' 'Balis,' 'Balles,' 'Balize,' 'Bellesse,' 'Bellize,' 'Belize,' 'Belice,' per {{harvnb|Ancona|1877|p=6, 10-12}}.</ref><ref group="note">Though the following alternatives have been proposed for the etymology of 'Belize'– # from French ''balise'' (lit. beacon), as in {{harvnb|Ancona|1877|pp=6, 9-12}} (quoting Squier), in {{harvnb|Bristowe|Wright|1888|p=23}}, in {{harvnb|Kinsbruner|Langer|2008|loc=second para}}, and in {{harvnb|Morris|1883|pp=12-13}}, # from Mayan ''belix'' (lit. muddy water) or ''belikin'' (lit. sea-facing land), as in {{harvnb|Griffith|Alford|Bolland|2022|loc=third para}}, and in {{harvnb|Kinsbruner|Langer|2008|loc=second para}}. </ref> Swallow Caye is similarly believed to be named after the ''Swallow''.{{sfn|Kinsbruner|Langer|2008|loc=first para}}
===Scholarly=== {{expand section|with=details about Wallace's possible identity and debate regarding his historicity|talk=Expandable?|date=April 2022}}
====Identity of Wallace==== It has been suggested that Wallace was– # the [[chief mate]] of [[Walter Raleigh]],{{sfn|Asturias|1925|p=7-9}} # ''Willis'', the Governor of the Anglo-French settlement of buccaneers in Tortuga,{{sfn|Ancona|1877|pp=12-14}}{{sfn|Winzerling|1946|pp=53-56}} # a settler of the [[Providence Island colony]].{{sfn|Craig|1969|p=55}}
====Wallace as apocryphal==== It has been suggested that Wallace is of doubtful historicity.{{sfn|Ancona|1878|p=373-374}}{{sfn|Bulmer-Thomas|Bulmer-Thomas|2016}}{{sfn|Humphreys|1961|p=1}}
